[[Category:Hawaii state parks]]

'''Kekaha Kai State Park''', also known as '''Kona Coast State Park''', is a located along the North [[Kona District, Hawaii|Kona coast]] on the island of [[Hawaii (island)|Hawai{{okina}}i]]. It includes '''Mahai{{okina}}ula Beach''', '''Makalawena Beach''' and '''Kua Bay'''. It is open 9:00am - 7:00pm daily except Wednesdays.<ref>http://hawaii.kulshan.com/Hawaii/Hawaii_County/The_Big_Island/Kalaoa/Outdoors/Kekaha_Kai_State_Park.htm</ref> A paved road 2.6 miles North of [[Kona International Airport]] leads to Manini{{okina}}owali (Kua Bay), and an unpaved lava road leads to Mahai{{okina}}ula.<ref>[http://www.co.hawaii.hi.us/planning/spa/north_kona/map1.html Official Coastal Access map] on County web site</ref> The Mahai{{okina}}ula section has a sandy beach and dune with a picnic area. A 4.5-mile hike north on the historic coastal trail, '''Ala Kahakai''', leads to Kua Bay. A hike to the summit of Pu'u Ku{{okina}}ili, a 342-foot high cinder cone, offers an excellent view of the coastline. <ref>[http://www.hawaiistateparks.org/parks/hawaii/Index.cfm?park_id=47 Kekaha Kai Page] on State Park official web site</ref>
