[[Category:Beaches of Hawaii (island)]] [[Category:Hawaii state parks]]

'''Kekaha Kai State Park''', formerly known as '''Kona Coast State Park''', is a located along the North [[Kona District, Hawaii|Kona coast]] on the island of [[Hawaii (island)|Hawai{{okina}}i]]. It includes '''Mahai{{okina}}ula Beach''', '''Makalawena Beach''' and '''Kua Bay'''. The wetland area around Makalawena<ref>[http://data.nodc.noaa.gov/coris/data/NOAA/nos/EnvironmentalSensitivityIndices/Hawaii/CDcontents/HI_PDFS/MAPS/HI23.PDF Envrironmental Sensitivity Index Map of Makalawena] on National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration web site</ref> is listed as a [[National Natural Landmark]]. It is one of the last remaining nesting grounds of the Hawaiian stilt, the Hawaiian coot, and the only known breeding area for the black-crowned night heron.<ref>[http://www.nature.nps.gov/nnl/registry/usa_map/states/hawaii/nnl/mm/index.cfm Makalawena Marsh] on National Park Service web site</ref> It is located at coordinates {{coord|19|47|32|N|156|1|31|W|display=inline,title}}.
The park is open 9:00am - 7:00pm daily except Wednesdays.<ref>http://hawaii.kulshan.com/Hawaii/Hawaii_County/The_Big_Island/Kalaoa/Outdoors/Kekaha_Kai_State_Park.htm</ref> A paved road 2.6 miles North of [[Kona International Airport]] leads to Manini{{okina}}owali (Kua Bay), and an unpaved lava road leads to Mahai{{okina}}ula.<ref>[http://www.co.hawaii.hi.us/planning/spa/north_kona/map1.html Official Coastal Access map] on County web site</ref> The Mahai{{okina}}ula section has a sandy beach and dune with a picnic area. A 4.5-mile hike north on the historic coastal trail, [[Ala Kahakai National Historic Trail|Ala Kahakai]], leads to Kua Bay. A hike to the summit of Pu{{okina}}u Ku{{okina}}ili, a 342-foot high cinder cone, offers an excellent view of the coastline. <ref>[http://www.hawaiistateparks.org/parks/hawaii/Index.cfm?park_id=47 Kekaha Kai Page] on State Park official web site</ref>
