{{coord missing|Hawaii}}
[[Category:Beaches of Hawaii (island)]] [[Category:Hawaii state parks]] [[Category: Hawaii (island)]]

'''Old Kona Airport State Recreation Area''' is a park built on the site of an old airport just North of [[Kailua, Hawaii County, Hawaii]]. When the much larger [[Kona International Airport]] was built at [[Keahole Point]] in 1970, the old landing strip built in 1948 near the town was used for drag racing before being turned into a park in 1976.<ref>[http://www.airfields-freeman.com/HI/Airfields_HI_Hawaii.htm Old Kona Airport] on Abandoned Airfields web site</ref>
The 103.7 acres of the old airport now include facilities run by the [[Hawaii County, Hawaii|County of Hawai{{okina}}i]].<ref>[http://www.hawaiistateparks.org/parks/hawaii/index.cfm?park_id=55 Old Kona Airport State Recreation Area] description on Hawaii State Park web site</ref> These include baseball and soccer fields, the '''Kona Community Aquatic Center''', and '''Kekuaokalani Gym''', located at 75-5530 Kuakini Highway.<ref>[http://www.hawaii-county.com/parks/konaaquaticspool.htm Kona Aquatic Center] Official web site</ref> A 217 acre marine preserve was created here in 1992. A day use boat mooring is near the prominent "Shark Rock" toward the northwestern boundary. Water depth at the mooring is about 40 feet.<ref>[http://hawaii.gov/dlnr/dar/coral/mlcd_old_kona.html Old Kona Airport] at the Marine Life Conservation District official web site</ref> A reef shelf East of Shark rock creates a small surf break. [[Snorkeling|Snorkle]]rs and [[Scuba diving|Scuba divers]] usually enter the water at a protected cove at the Northwestern end of the beach. On '''Kuka{{okina}}ilimoku Point''' Southeast of the park sits a lighthouse to guide ships into Kailua Bay.
The old 3800 foot long runway is used for a large parking lot and the old terminal building is now a public use pavilion. There is a flat walking trail parallel to the runway, restrooms, showers, and picnic facilities. There are some patches of sand, but the shore is rocky, so care should be taken when entering the water except in calm conditions. No lifeguards are on duty.
